{"type":"message","id":"1f572f05","parentId":"af1a15f7","timestamp":"2026-03-23T23:28:34.971Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK now I have a very full picture. Zach has an enormous codebase with many projects:\n\n- `C:\\dev\\notebooks\\` - 9 notebooks\n- `C:\\dev\\neu-project\\notebooks\\` - 5 notebooks (same names as above!)\n- `C:\\dev\\research\\` - various projects with notebooks\n- `C:\\dev\\infant\\` - colab notebook\n- `C:\\dev\\time\\` - time series related notebooks\n- `C:\\dev\\EXP\\` - production stuff\n- `C:\\Claw\\` - 2 notebooks\n\nThe key issues I can see:\n1. **Massive duplication** between `C:\\dev\\notebooks\\` and `C:\\dev\\neu-project\\notebooks\\` (they share identical filenames - 01_train_baselines.ipynb, 02_train_neu_routing.ipynb, etc.)\n\n\n2. **Scattered across the filesystem** - research, time, infant, EXP, and Claw all have their own notebook collections\n3. **Unclear which versions are current** - I need to figure out which notebooks are actively being worked on versus archived\n\nI should audit these properly by identifying duplicates, checking file sizes and modification times to determine what's live, and then consolidating everything into one organized location. Zach's been working on consolidating his codebase for a while now, so this is part of that ongoing cleanup effort.\n\nLooking at the notebooks themselves, I can see there are five training and evaluation scripts for the neu-project spread across `C:\\dev\\notebooks\\` and `C:\\dev\\neu-project\\notebooks\\` with identical names - likely due to a refactoring where the project structure changed but old copies weren't cleaned up.\n\nBeyond those, there are several standalone notebooks for different experiments: attention and SRMoE training in the root `C:\\dev\\` directory, infant gym experiments, gradient wool learning for the mmm project, and a kaggle-finetune notebook for smollm3.\n\nThen there's a whole set in the neu-project noteboo