{"type":"message","id":"218e0469","parentId":"cd4dce8b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:42:16.367Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Actually wait - I need to also keep `import wandb` on the same line as the `class SRMoETrainer:` line? No, that's wrong. Let me re-read the code. In the original notebook, `import wandb` was added as a separate element. But actually, looking at the error, it seems the source was joined into a single line. The issue was that the patch script stored `[src]` where `src` is a single string. The notebook format actually requires `source` to be a list of strings (one per line), OR a single string (which gets treated as one line). The patch stored a single string with embedded `\\n` as `[single_string]`, which Jupyter reads as one long line.\n\n\nNow I'm realizing the real problem - when `cell['source'] = [src]` stores a single string with embedded newlines, Jupyter interprets those newlines as line continuations within that one cell, so the code ends up on a single logical line. That's why the syntax error mentions line 2 rather than showing the full concatenated content.\n\nThe fix is to split the source string by actual newlines and store it as a proper list of strings, so each line becomes its own element in the source array.","thinkingSignature":"0110b2b04e9d7efc59a0bc4cce16332fd965fabef58916a6ccc0dcc94bc23249"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_zc8hhvqrs71u_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\fix_cell5.py\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":55873,"output":307,"cacheRead":13804,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":69984,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774312926748}}
