{"type":"message","id":"6caf740c","parentId":"b6c78453","timestamp":"2026-03-24T01:18:42.579Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I made the same mistake again - storing the source as a single string in cell['source'] = [src]. I need to be more careful. Let me rewrite this to properly build the notebook-format source list.\n\nActually wait - looking at my previous fixes, the problem was that when I stored `[src]` (a single string), Jupyter would display the entire source as one line (the `\\n` characters in the string don't create new lines in the cell display). But when the source is stored as a list of strings (one per line), Jupyter properly shows line breaks.\n\nHowever, I noticed in my `fix_cell5_v3.py` that when I did:\n\n\n```\nnb_source = [l + '\\n' for l in lines[:-1]] if lines[-1] == '' else [l + '\\n' for l in lines]\n```\n\nThis actually worked - the cell displayed correctly with proper line breaks. But my verification script showed that `joined = ''.join(cell['source'])` followed by `split('\\n')` would NOT recreate the same number of lines because of trailing newline handling. This discrepancy confused me earlier, so I need to be really precise about how I'm constructing and verifying the source list.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a fundamental issue here: when I store source as `[src]` where `src` is a single concatenated string with embedded newlines, the JSON representation preserves those `\\n` characters inside the string. But when Jupyter reads this, it doesn't split on `\\n` to create separate lines - it just displays the entire string as one block. My verification approach was flawed because I was joining and splitting the string, which gave me a line count that didn't match what Jupyter actually displays. The real question is whether Jupyter correctly interprets the embedded newlines when the source is stored as a single string in the JSON.","thinkingSignature":"0ed4c09d8ebc978701562e6ec0eb0d8174