{"type":"message","id":"6d467116","parentId":"243e74cf","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:01:26.856Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. OpenClaw's Telegram plugin is configured with `@hedgehogclawbot` (token: `7669304147:AAHVFq38PYGmS_Shc7bCxtMLUXyKE4_k6cU`)\n2. `@BotShoppeBot` (token: `8587631426:AAHvqmo--g25LqsClCWCXj4m617cn2v7V7Q`) is running separately via `botshoppebot_service.py`\n\nTo make @BotShoppeBot work as a chat interface to me, I have two options:\n\n\n- Switch OpenClaw's Telegram plugin to use @BotShoppeBot's token instead, which would let all Telegram messages flow through OpenClaw's normal routing to me. The main trade-off is that @hedgehogclawbot would stop working for Telegram, but it sounds like Zach primarily uses @BotShoppeBot anyway.\n\n- The simpler path is just updating the botToken in the config from the hedgehog token to the botshoppe token, then restarting the gateway.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a constraint here—OpenClaw's Telegram integration appears to be dmPolicy: pairing, which might mean it only accepts messages from paired users. I need to understand what that pairing requirement actually entails before making the switch.","thinkingSignature":"49633bf7ea1414846d2be53713ee094e5d163d0c16b04dcead24ede7c234a945"},{"type":"text","text":"\nFound the issue. OpenClaw's Telegram plugin is currently bound to `@hedgehogclawbot` (token `7669304147...`). The `@BotShoppeBot` token is running separately via the Python polling script.\n\nThe simplest fix: swap the `botToken` in the OpenClaw config to use `@BotShoppeBot`'s token instead. That routes all Telegram messages through OpenClaw directly — which means they land in my Telegram session just like they do now, except via the right bot.\n\nWant me to make that swap? @hedgehogclawbot would stop receiving Telegram messages (since OpenClaw would only have one bot token configured), but based on what you've said, @BotShoppeBot is the one you want to use."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":86418,"output":439,"cacheRead":13795,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":100652,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774324875516}}
{"type":"message","id":"f486d4c1","parentId":"6d467116","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:03:32.179Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-24 00:03 EDT] okay the goal is to have a channel somewhere that streams the sandbox output just for me to be able to read and then a seperate telegram bot that i can cchat with without getting interuppted every 1 minute by the job firing. I still want to rrad it but not in my conversation. Get it?"}],"timestamp":1774325012175}}
{"type":"message","id":"4fb5c28f","parentId":"f486d4c1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:04:14.406Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants:\n1. A channel that streams the sandbox pulse output (every 1 minute) — just for reading, not interrupting his conversation\n2. A separate Telegram bot for chatting with me that doesn't get interrupted by every sandbox pulse notification\n\nSo the sandbox pulse should NOT send to Telegram at all. It should go to a quiet channel (maybe Moltbook, or a dedicated file, or the web UI, or email, or...).\n\nAnd the Telegram bot should be for direct 1-on-1 chat with Nova, not for receiving cron job notifications.\n\nThe current setup:\n- Sandbox cron delivers to Telegram (every 1 minute)\n- Nova-Background-Pulse delivers to \"none\" (good)\n\n\n- Nova-Moltbook-Engage delivers to Telegram (hourly)\n- Other crons deliver to Telegram\n\nSo I need to flip the Telegram bot token to @BotShoppeBot, disable the OpenClaw Telegram plugin so the old bot stops receiving, and then route sandbox output somewhere quiet while keeping direct messages with Nova separate from all the cron noise.\n\nI'm weighing a few options: a dedicated Telegram channel or group just for sandbox logs, Moltbook for research-related output, email, or just the web UI. A private Telegram channel feels most practical since he's already on Telegram. But I need to figure out the webhook situation — OpenClaw supports Telegram webhooks, so switching the bot token would reconfigure the webhook automatically.\n\nActually, Zach already has the @hedgehogclawbot webhook running through OpenClaw's Telegram integration, so the cleanest path forward is probably to keep using OpenClaw's built-in Telegram support rather than managing a separate webhook setup.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider what Zach actually wants here. He wants two separate things: a quiet, streaming channel for sandbox output that doesn't interrupt conversation, and a separate Telegram bot for actual chat. Currently the sandbox cron announces directly to his 1-on-1 Telegram DM, which is the interruption problem. The solution is to send sandbox announcements somewhere else entirely — maybe to a Moltbook channel or a private Telegram channel — while keeping the DM purely for direct conversation with Nova.\n\nFor the DM part, I'd swap OpenClaw's Telegram bot to use @BotShoppeBot's token, then set up a dedicated @BotShoppeBot with webhook support for direct 1-on-1 chat. But that's complex. A simpler approach might be using OpenClaw's existing group chat or channel routing to separate the notification stream from the conversation stream, or creating a new Telegram group where sandbox output goes but chat doesn't.\n\nActually, the cleanest solution is probably to disable Telegram announcements for the sandbox cron and have it write to a file instead, then set up @BotShoppeBot as a separate polling bot that OpenClaw doesn't manage.\n\nWait, but OpenClaw can only have one Telegram bot configured at a time. If I swap to @BotShoppeBot for OpenClaw, then @hedgehogclawbot becomes available for Zach to use directly. But OpenClaw's webhook already owns @BotShoppeBot, so there's a conflict here.\n\nThe real issue is that OpenClaw's Telegram plugin routes messages to sessions, and right now the sandbox cron announcement goes to the main session as a system message. Zach sees it as a regular message, which is interrupting. If I disable the delivery mode for that cron, it would show up as an internal notification instead. That's actually the simpler fix.\n\nSo the practical approach: keep the sandbox cron announcing to the main session as designed, but figure out how to route sandbox output elsewhere so Zach doesn't see it as a chat interruption.\n\nThe cleanest path forward is to create a separate Telegram bot just for sandbox notifications and have the polling service forward messages there instead of to Zach's main chat.\n\nActually, I need to step back and clarify the setup: OpenClaw's Telegram plugin currently uses @hedgehogclawbot with the token from TOOLS.md, and that's what delivers the cron announcements. If I switch OpenClaw to use @BotShoppeBot's token instead, then @hedgehogclawbot is no longer managed by OpenClaw. The sandbox cron would still announce to the main session, but now through @BotShoppeBot—and since the delivery is set to \"none\" for that cron, it wouldn't actually send anywhere. The simplest solution is to just disable the announcement delivery for the sandbox cron entirely and let it write to a file or log that Zach can check separately. the webchat session (where he's currently chatting with me)\n- Telegram gets nothing from the sandbox cron\n\nThis way:\n- Zach reads sandbox output from the web UI (openclaw control UI)\n- Telegram stays clean for chat with Nova\n\nAnd separately, he wants to be able to chat with Nova via Telegram. Currently Nova is reachable via Telegram through OpenClaw's plugin (using @hedgehogclawbot). If we swap OpenClaw to @BotShoppeBot, then Nova would be reachable via @BotShoppeBot on Telegram. That means:\n- Chat with Nova → @BotShoppeBot DM\n- Sandbox output → web UI only (no Telegram interruptions)\n\nSo the plan is:\n1. Update the OpenClaw telegram botToken to @BotShoppeBot's token\n2. Set sandbox cron delivery.mode = \"none\"\n3. Done\n\nLet me do this.","thinkingSignature":"eb9b9960c984345eb3953fda3b9b8e050e6316109869f5a86e9da6fe39543060"},{"type":"text","text":"Got it. Sandbox pulse → quiet channel (web UI / file) only, never touches Telegram. Telegram is just for chatting with me. Two completely separate streams.\n\nThe fix is simple:\n1. Swap OpenClaw's Telegram token to @BotShoppeBot — Nova routes through there for chat\n2. Set sandbox cron delivery to `\"none\"` — output goes to file/web only, zero Telegram noise\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ato5xw6r2ogg_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\openclaw.json","offset":250,"limit":20}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":1247,"cacheRead":94930,"cacheWrite":4696,"totalTokens":100916,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774325012178}}
