{"type":"message","id":"db98f543","parentId":"f556e7b8","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:41:45.468Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking a very real question - even with a self-hosted proxy, you still need GPU compute to run the actual LLM inference. You can't run a capable LLM on CPU alone.\n\nLet me think about what options exist for truly self-hosted, GPU-independent inference:\n\n1. **Run your own GPU** - you have the RTX 5000 in your machine, but it's not always on\n2. **Paperspace** - but you said their 6-hour wind-down is annoying and not always-on\n3. **Cheaper cloud GPU** - Hetzner, Vast.ai, RunPod, etc.\n4. **Use a model that can run on CPU** - smaller models, but not the same capability\n\n\n5. **Distributed/self-healing GPU farm** - could pool resources, but that's a whole infrastructure problem\n\nThe core constraint is physics - capable models need GPU memory and compute, and you're either paying for it or running it yourself. The KVict proxy itself is just routing, so that part doesn't need a GPU at all. The real question is whether you want to pay for cloud GPU access, run it locally on your RTX 5000, or explore something like Groq's inference layer which might be cheaper than direct GPU costs.","thinkingSignature":"af71fa9a00ace9877b34f593e247f72c325c13b5b27537ce12d942b70532befb"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Yeah, it does. Smaller models can run on CPU (7B params, maybe 4-bit quant) but you're not running anything close to M2.7 on CPU without it being painfully slow.\n\nThe options:\n\n1. **Your RTX 5000** — always-on desktop GPU, but your machine has to be on and not sleeping\n2. **Cheaper cloud GPU** — Vast.ai, RunPod, Hetzner. Hourly billing, way cheaper than Paperspace for intermittent use. You could spin up a GPU instance when the sandbox pulses, not pay when it's idle\n3. **Groq** — they have inference hardware with fast throughput, no GPU you manage, competitive pricing. API access is corporate but the hardware is theirs\n4. **Ollama + Modal** — you already have Ollama on Modal, Modal gives you GPU on demand. Your `modal_spark.py` already starts Ollama on request. This is actually the closest to what you want — Modal handles the GPU provisioning, you just pay for compute time\n\nFor the sandbox pulse specifically (stateless, ~30s per run), spinning up a cloud GPU per pulse would cost more than it saves. The real win is having a cheap always-on CPU instance that routes to a GPU endpoint when needed.\n\nWhat matters most — minimizing cost, minimizing corporate dependency, or minimizing infrastructure complexity?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":547,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":104067,"totalTokens":108903,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774327285880}}
